{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}So Jesus told them this parable \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}\uc1\u8216*Who among you who has a hundred sheep, and has lost one of them, does not leave the ninety-nine out in the open country, and go after the lost sheep until he finds it?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And, when he has found it, he puts in on his shoulders rejoicing;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}and, on reaching home, he calls his friends and his neighbours together, and says \uc1\u8220*Come and rejoice with me, for I have found my sheep which was lost.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}So, I tell you, there will be more rejoicing in heaven over one outcast who repents, than over ninety-nine religious people, who have no need to repent.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Or again, what woman who has ten silver coins, if she loses one of them, does not light a lamp, and sweep the house, and search carefully until she finds it?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And, when she has found it, she calls her friends and neighbours together, and says \uc1\u8220*Come and rejoice with me, for I have found the coin which I lost.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}So, I tell you, there is rejoicing in the presence of God\uc1\u8217*s angels over one outcast who repents.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then Jesus continued, \uc1\u8216*A man had two sons;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}and the younger of them said to his father \uc1\u8220*Father, give me my share of the inheritance.\uc1\u8221* So the father divided the property between them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}A few days later the younger son got together all that he had, and went away into a distant land; and there he squandered his inheritance by leading a dissolute life.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}After he has spent all that he had, there was a severe famine through all that country, and he began to be in actual want.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}So he went and engaged himself to one of the people of that country, who sent him into his fields to tend pigs.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}He even longed to satisfy his hunger with the bean-pods on which the pigs were feeding; and no one gave him anything.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}But, when he came to himself, he said \uc1\u8220*How many of my father\uc1\u8217*s hired servants have more bread than they can eat, while here am I starving to death!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}I will get up and go to my father, and say to him \uc1\u8216*Father, I sinned against heaven and against you;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}I am no longer fit to be called your son; make me one of your hired servants.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And he got up and went to his father. But, while he was still a long way off, his father saw him and was deeply moved; he ran and threw his arms round his neck and kissed him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}\uc1\u8220*Father,\uc1\u8221* the son said, \uc1\u8220*I sinned against heaven and against you; I am no longer fit to be called your son; make me one of your hired servants.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}But the father turned to his servants and said \uc1\u8220*Be quick and fetch a robe \uc1\u8211* the very best \uc1\u8211* and put it on him; give him a ring for his finger and sandals for his feet;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}and bring the fattened calf and kill it, and let us eat and make merry;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}for here is my son who was dead, and is alive again, was lost, and is found.\uc1\u8221* So they began making merry.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Meanwhile the elder son was out in the fields; but, on coming home, when he got near the house, he heard music and dancing,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}and he called one of the servants and asked what it all meant.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}\uc1\u8220*Your brother has come back,\uc1\u8221* the servant told him, \uc1\u8220*and your father has killed the fattened calf, because he has him back safe and sound.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}This made him angry, and he would not go in. But his father came out and begged him to do so.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}\uc1\u8220*No,\uc1\u8221* he said to his father, \uc1\u8220*look at all the years I have been serving you, without ever once disobeying you, and yet you have never given me even a young goat, so that I might have a party with my friends.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}But, no sooner has this son of yours come, who has eaten up your property in the company of prostitutes, than you have killed the fattened calf for him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}\uc1\u8220*Child,\uc1\u8221* the father answered, \uc1\u8220*you are always with me, and everything that I have is yours.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}We could but make merry and rejoice, for here is your brother who was dead, and is alive; who was lost, and is found.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 16}Jesus said to his disciples, \uc1\u8216*There was a rich man who had a steward; and this steward was maliciously accused to him of wasting his estate.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}So the master called him and said \uc1\u8220*What is this that I hear about you? Give in your accounts, for you cannot act as steward any longer.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}\uc1\u8220*What am I to do,\uc1\u8221* the steward asked himself, \uc1\u8220*now that my master is taking the steward\uc1\u8217*s place away from me? I have not strength to dig, and I am ashamed to beg.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}I know what I will do, so that, as soon as I am turned out of my stewardship, people may welcome me into their homes.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}One by one he called up his master\uc1\u8217*s debtors. \uc1\u8220*How much do you owe my master?\uc1\u8221* he asked of the first.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}\uc1\u8220*Four hundred and forty gallons of oil,\uc1\u8221* answered the man. \uc1\u8220*Here is your agreement,\uc1\u8221* he said; \uc1\u8220*sit down at once and make it two hundred and twenty.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And you, the steward said to the next, \uc1\u8220*how much do you owe?\uc1\u8221* \uc1\u8220*Seventy quarters of wheat,\uc1\u8221* he replied. \uc1\u8220*Here is your agreement,\uc1\u8221* the steward said; \uc1\u8220*make it fifty-six.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}His master complimented this dishonest steward on the shrewdness of his action. And indeed men of the world are shrewder in dealing with their fellow men than those who have the light.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And I say to you \uc1\u8220*Win friends for yourselves with your dishonest money,\uc1\u8221* so that, when it comes to an end, there may be a welcome for you into the Eternal Home.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}The person who is trustworthy in the smallest matter is trustworthy in a great one also; and the person who is dishonest in the smallest matter is dishonest in a great one also.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}So, if you have proved untrustworthy with the dishonest money, who will trust you with the true?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And, if you have proved untrustworthy with what does not belong to us, who will give you what is really our own?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}No servant can serve two masters, for, either they will hate one and love the other, or else they will attach themselves to one and despise the other. You cannot serve both God and money.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}All this was said within hearing of the Pharisees, who were lovers of money, and they began to sneer at Jesus.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}\uc1\u8216*You,\uc1\u8217* said Jesus, \uc1\u8216*are the ones who justify themselves before the world, but God can read your hearts; and what is highly esteemed among people may be an abomination in the sight of God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}The Law and the prophets sufficed until the time of John. Since then the good news of the kingdom of God has been told, and everybody has been forcing their way into it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}It would be easier for the heavens and the earth to disappear than for one stroke of a letter in the Law to be lost.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Everyone who divorces his wife and marries another woman is an adulterer, and the man who marries a divorced woman is an adulterer.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}There was once a rich man, who dressed in purple robes and fine linen, and feasted every day in great splendour.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Near his gateway there had been laid a beggar named Lazarus, who was covered with sores,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}and who longed to satisfy his hunger with what fell from the rich man\uc1\u8217*s table. Even the dogs came and licked his sores.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}After a time the beggar died, and was taken by the angels to be with Abraham. The rich man also died and was buried.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}In Hades he looked up in his torment, and saw Abraham at a distance and Lazarus at his side.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}So he called out \uc1\u8220*Pity me, Father Abraham, and send Lazarus to dip the tip of his finger in water and cool my tongue, for I am suffering agony in this flame.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}\uc1\u8220*Child,\uc1\u8221* answered Abraham, \uc1\u8220*remember that you in your lifetime received what you thought desirable, just as Lazarus received what was not desirable; but now he has his consolation here, while you are suffering agony.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}And not only that, but between you and us there lies a great chasm, so that those who wish to pass from here to you cannot, nor can they cross from there to us.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}\uc1\u8220*Then, Father,\uc1\u8221* he said, \uc1\u8220*I beg you to send Lazarus to my father\uc1\u8217*s house \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}For I have five brothers to warn them, so that they may not come to this place of torture also.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}\uc1\u8220*They have the writings of Moses and the prophets,\uc1\u8221* replied Abraham; \uc1\u8220*let them listen to them.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}\uc1\u8220*But, Father Abraham,\uc1\u8221* he urged, \uc1\u8220*if someone from the dead were to go to them, they would repent.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}\uc1\u8220*If they do not listen to Moses and the prophets,\uc1\u8221* answered Abraham, \uc1\u8220*they will not be persuaded, even if someone were to rise from the dead.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 17}Jesus said to his disciples, \uc1\u8216*It is inevitable that there should be temptations but sorrow awaits the person who does the tempting!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}It would be better for them if they had been flung into the sea with a millstone round their neck, rather than that they should cause even one of these little ones to stumble.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Be on your guard! If your brother or sister does wrong, rebuke them; but if they repent, forgive them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Even if they wrong you seven times a day, but turns to you every time and says \uc1\u8220*I am sorry,\uc1\u8221* you must forgive them.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}\uc1\u8216*Give us more faith,\uc1\u8217* said the apostles to the Master;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}but the Master said, \uc1\u8216*If your faith were only like a mustard seed, you could say to this mulberry tree \uc1\u8220*Be uprooted and planted in the sea,\uc1\u8221* and it would obey you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Which of you, if he had a servant ploughing, or tending the sheep, would say to him, when he came in from the fields, \uc1\u8220*Come at once and take your place at the table,\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Instead of saying \uc1\u8220*Prepare my dinner, and then make yourself ready and serve me while I am eating and drinking, and after that you will eat and drink yourself\uc1\u8221*?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Does he feel grateful to his servant for doing what he is told?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And so with you \uc1\u8211* when you have done all that you have been told, still say \uc1\u8220*We are but useless servants; we have done no more than we ought to have done.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217*
\par}

