{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 13}Among the members of the church at Antioch there were several prophets and teachers \uc1\u8211* Barnabas, Simeon who was known by the name of \uc1\u8220*Black\uc1\u8221*, Lucius of Cyrene, Manaen, foster-brother of Prince Herod, and Saul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}While they were engaged in the worship of the Lord and were fasting, the Holy Spirit said, \uc1\u8216*Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul, for the work to which I have called them.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Accordingly, after fasting and prayer, they placed their hands on them and dismissed them.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Barnabas and Saul, sent on this mission, as they were, by the Holy Spirit, went down to Seleucia, and from there sailed to Cyprus.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}On reaching Salamis, they began to tell the message of God in the Jewish synagogues; and they had John with them as an assistant.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}After passing through the whole island, they reached Paphos, where they found an astrologer who pretended to be a prophet \uc1\u8211* a Jew by birth, whose name was Barjoshua.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}He was at the court of the Governor, Sergius Paulus, a man of intelligence, who sent for Barnabas and Saul and asked to be told God\uc1\u8217*s message.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}But Elymas, the astrologer (for that is the meaning of the word), opposed them, eager to divert the Governor\uc1\u8217*s attention from the faith.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}However, Saul (who is the same as Paul), full of the Holy Spirit, fixed his eyes on him and said,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}\uc1\u8216*You incarnation of deceit and all fraud! You son of the devil! You opponent of all that is good! Will you never cease to divert the straight paths of the Lord? Listen!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}The hand of the Lord is on you even now, and you will be blind for a time and unable to see the sun.\uc1\u8217* Immediately a mist and darkness fell on him, and he went feeling about for someone to guide him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}When the Governor saw what had happened, he became a believer in Christ, being greatly impressed by the teaching about the Lord.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}After this, Paul and his companions set sail from Paphos and went to Perga in Pamphylia, where John left them and returned to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}The others went on from Perga and arrived at Antioch in Pisidia. There they went into the synagogue on the Sabbath and took their seats.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}After the reading of the Law and the prophets, the synagogue leader sent them this message \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*Friends, if you have any helpful words to address to the people, now is the time to speak.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}So Paul rose and, motioning with his hand, said:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*People of Israel and all here who worship God, hear what I have to say.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}The God of this people Israel chose our ancestors, and during their stay in Egypt increased the prosperity of the people, and then with uplifted arm brought them out from that land.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}For about forty years he bore with them in the desert;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}then, after destroying seven heathen nations in Canaan, he allotted their land to this people \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}For about four hundred and fifty years. In later times he gave them Judges, of whom the prophet Samuel was the last.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And, when they demanded a king, God gave them Saul the son of Kish, a man of the tribe of Benjamin, who reigned for forty years.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}After removing him, he raised David to the throne, and bore this testimony to him \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*In David, the son of Jesse, I have found a man after my own heart, who will carry out all my purposes.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}It was from this man\uc1\u8217*s descendants that God, in accordance with his promise, gave Israel a Saviour \uc1\u8211* Jesus;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}John having first proclaimed, before the appearance of Jesus, a baptism on repentance for all the people of Israel.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}As John was drawing towards the end of his career, he said \uc1\u8220*What do you suppose that I am? I am not the Christ. But there is \uc1\u8216*one coming\uc1\u8217* after me, whose sandal I am not worthy to untie.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Brothers and sisters, descendants of Abraham, and all those among you who worship God, it was to us that the message of this salvation was sent.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}The people of Jerusalem and their leaders, failing to recognise Jesus, and not understanding the utterances of the prophets that are read every Sabbath, fulfilled them by condemning him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}They found no ground at all for putting him to death, and yet demanded his execution from Pilate;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}and, after carrying out everything written about him, they took Jesus down from the cross, and laid him in a tomb.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}But God raised him from the dead;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}and he appeared for many days to those who had gone up with him from Galilee to Jerusalem, and who are now witnesses for him to the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}We also have good news to tell you, about the promise made to our ancestors \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}That our children have had this promise completely fulfilled to them by God, by his raising Jesus. That is just what is said in the second Psalm \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*You are my Son; this day I have become your Father.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}As to his raising Jesus from the dead, never again to return to corruption, this is what is said \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*I will give to you the sacred promises made to David;\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}And, therefore, in another Psalm it is said \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*You will not give up the Holy One to undergo corruption.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}David, after obediently doing God\uc1\u8217*s will in his own time, fell asleep and was laid by the side of his ancestors, and did undergo corruption;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}but Jesus, whom God raised from the dead, did not undergo corruption.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}I would, therefore, like you to know, friends, that through Jesus forgiveness of sins is being proclaimed to you,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}and that, in union with him, everyone who believes in him is absolved from every sin from which under the Law of Moses you could not be absolved.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}Beware, therefore, that what is said in the prophets does not come true of you \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 41}\uc1\u8220*Look, you despisers, and wonder, and perish;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
for I am doing a deed in your days \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
a deed which, though told you in full, you will never believe\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 42}As Paul and Barnabas were leaving the synagogue, the people begged for a repetition of this teaching on the next Sabbath.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 43}After the congregation had dispersed, many of the Jews, and of the converts who joined in their worship, followed Paul and Barnabas, who talked with them and urged them to continue to rely on the loving kindness of God.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 44}On the following Sabbath, almost all the city gathered to hear God\uc1\u8217*s message.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 45}But the sight of the crowds of people filled the minds of the Jews with jealousy, and they kept contradicting Paul\uc1\u8217*s statements in violent language.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 46}Then Paul and Barnabas spoke out fearlessly, and said:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*It was necessary that the message of God should be told to you first; but, since you reject it and reckon yourselves not worthy of the eternal life \uc1\u8211* we turn to the Gentiles!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 47}For this is the Lord\uc1\u8217*s command to us \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*I have destined you for a light to the Gentiles,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
a means of salvation to the ends of the earth\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 48}On hearing this, the Gentiles were glad and extolled God\uc1\u8217*s message; and all those who had been enrolled for eternal life became believers in Christ;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 49}and the Lord\uc1\u8217*s message was carried throughout that district.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 50}But the Jews incited the women of high social standing who worshiped with them, and the leading men of the town, and started a persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and drove them out of their region.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 51}They, however, shook the dust off their feet in protest,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 52}and went to Iconium, leaving the disciples full of joy and of the Holy Spirit.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 14}The same thing occurred in Iconium, where Paul and Barnabas went into the Jewish synagogue, and spoke in such a way that a great number of both Jews and Greeks believed in Christ.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}But the Jews who refused to believe stirred up the Gentiles, and poisoned their minds against the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Therefore Paul and Barnabas spent a long time there, and spoke out fearlessly, relying on the Lord, who confirmed the message of his love by permitting signs and wonders to take place at their hands.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}But the townspeople were divided, some siding with the Jews, some with the apostles;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}and, when there was an attempt on the part of both Gentiles and Jews, with their leaders, to resort to violence and to stone them,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}the apostles heard of it, and took refuge in Lystra and Derbe, towns in Lycaonia, and in the district round,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}and there they continued to tell the good news.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}In the streets of Lystra there used to sit a man who had no power in his feet; he had been lame from his birth, and had never walked.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}This man was listening to Paul speaking, when Paul, looking intently at him, and seeing that he had the faith to be healed,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}said loudly, \uc1\u8216*Stand upright on your feet.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
The man leaped up, and began walking about,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}and the crowd, seeing what Paul had done, called out in the Lycaonian language, \uc1\u8216*The Gods have come down to us in human form.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}So they called Barnabas \uc1\u8220*Zeus,\uc1\u8221* and Paul \uc1\u8220*Hermes,\uc1\u8221* because he took the lead in speaking;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}and the priest of Zeus-beyond-the-Walls, accompanied by the crowd, brought bullocks and garlands to the gates, with the intention of offering sacrifices.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}But, when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard of it, they tore their clothes and rushed out into the crowd.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Friends, why are you doing this?\uc1\u8217* they shouted.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}\uc1\u8216*We are only people like yourselves, and we have come with the good news that you should turn away from these follies to a living God, who made the heavens, the earth, the sea, and everything that is in them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}In bygone times he permitted all the nations to go their own ways.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Yet he has not failed to give you, in the good he does, some revelation of himself \uc1\u8211* sending you from heaven rain and fruitful seasons, and gladdening your hearts with plenty and good cheer.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Even with this appeal they could hardly restrain the people from offering sacrifice to them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Presently, however, there came some Jews from Antioch, and Iconium who, after they had won over the people, stoned Paul, and dragged him out of the town, thinking him to be dead.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}But, when the disciples had gathered round him, he got up and went back into the town; the next day he went with Barnabas to Derbe.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}After telling the good news throughout that town, and making a number of converts, they returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}reassuring the minds of the disciples, urging them to remain true to the faith, and showing that it is only through many troubles that we can enter the kingdom of God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}They also appointed elders for them in every church, and, after prayer and fasting, commended them to the Lord in whom they had learned to believe.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Paul and Barnabas then went through Pisidia, and came into Pamphylia,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}and, after telling the message at Perga, went down to Attaleia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}From there they sailed to Antioch \uc1\u8211* the place where they had been committed to the gracious care of God for the work which they had now finished.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}After their arrival, they gathered the church together, and gave an account of all that God had helped them to do, and especially how he had opened to the Gentiles the door of faith;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}and at Antioch they stayed with the disciples for a considerable time.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 15}But certain persons came down from Judea, and began to teach the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers that, unless they were circumcised, in accordance with the custom required by Moses, they could not be saved.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}This gave rise to a serious dispute, and much discussion, between Paul and Barnabas and these people, and it was therefore settled that Paul and Barnabas and others of their number should go up to Jerusalem, to consult the apostles and church elders about the matter under discussion.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}The church, therefore, sent them on their journey, and they made their way through Phoenicia and Samaria, telling the story of the conversion of the Gentiles, to the great joy of all the followers.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}On their arrival at Jerusalem, they were welcomed by the church, as well as by the apostles and the elders, and gave an account of all that God had helped them to do.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Some of the Pharisees\uc1\u8217* party, however, who had become believers in Christ, came forward and declared that they were bound to circumcise converts and to direct them to observe the Law of Moses.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}The apostles and the church elders held a meeting to consider this question.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}After much discussion, Peter rose and said:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*You, my friends, know well that long ago God singled me out \uc1\u8211* that through my lips the Gentiles should hear the message of the good news, and become believers in Christ.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Now God, who reads all hearts, declared his acceptance of the Gentiles, by giving them the Holy Spirit, just as he did to us.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}He made no distinction between them and us, when he purified their hearts by their faith.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Why, then, do you now provoke God, by putting on the necks of these disciples a yoke which neither our ancestors nor we were able to bear?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}No, it is through the loving kindness of the Lord Jesus that we, just as they do, believe that we have been saved.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Every voice in the assembly was hushed, as they listened to Barnabas and Paul, while they gave an account of all the signs and wonders which God had shown among the Gentiles through them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}After they had finished speaking, James addressed the Council.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Friends,\uc1\u8217* he began, \uc1\u8216*hear what I have to say.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Simon has described the manner in which God first visited the Gentiles, in order to take from among them a people to bear his name.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And that is in harmony with the words of the prophets, where they say \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}\uc1\u8220*After this I will return;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
and I will rebuild the house of David which has fallen \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
its ruins I will rebuild,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
and will set it up once more;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}that so the rest of mankind may earnestly seek the Lord \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
even all the Gentiles on whom my name has been bestowed,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}says the Lord, as he does these things, known from long ago.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}In my judgment, therefore, we should not add to the difficulties of those Gentiles who are turning to God,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}but we should write to them to abstain from food that has been polluted by being sacrificed to idols, from impurity, from eating the flesh of strangled animals, and from blood.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}For in every town, for generations past, there have been those who preach Moses, read as he is in the synagogues every Sabbath.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}It was then decided by the apostles and the elders, with the assent of the whole church, to choose some of their number, and send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas. Those chosen were Judas (called Barsabas) and Silas, who were leaders among the community.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}They were bearers of the following letter \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*The apostles, and the followers who are the church elders, send their greetings to the followers of the Lord of Gentile birth in Antioch, Syria, and Cilicia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}As we had heard that some of our number had upset you by their assertions, and unsettled your minds \uc1\u8211* without instructions from us \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}We met and decided to choose certain men and send them to you with our dear friends Barnabas and Paul,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord, Jesus Christ.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}We are accordingly sending Judas and Silas, and they will tell you by word of mouth what we are now writing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}We have, therefore, decided, under the guidance of the Holy Spirit, to lay no further burden on you beyond these necessary conditions \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}That you abstain from food offered to idols, from blood, from eating the flesh of strangled animals, and from impurity. If you guard yourselves against such things, it will be well with you. Farewell.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}So the bearers of this letter were sent on their way, and went down to Antioch. There they called a meeting of all the followers,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}and delivered the letter, the reading of which caused great rejoicing by its encouraging contents.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}Judas and Silas, who were themselves prophets, further encouraged the them by many an address, and strengthened their faith.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}After some stay, they were dismissed with kind farewells from the followers, and returned to those who had sent them.{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}  Some later manuscripts add: But Silas decided to stay. }
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}Paul and Barnabas, however, remained in Antioch, where they taught and, with the help of many others, told the good news of the Lord\uc1\u8217*s message.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}Some time after this, Paul said to Barnabas, \uc1\u8216*Let us go back and visit the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers in every town in which we have told the Lord\uc1\u8217*s message, and see how they are prospering.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}Barnabas wished to take with them John, whose other name was Mark;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}but Paul felt that they ought not to take with them the man who had deserted them in Pamphylia, and had not gone on with them to their work.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}This caused such unpleasant feeling between them that they parted ways, Barnabas taking Mark and sailing for Cyprus,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}while Paul chose Silas for his companion and, after he had been committed by the followers to the gracious care of the Lord,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 41}started on his journey and went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches in the faith.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 16}Among other places Paul went to Derbe and Lystra. At the latter place they found a disciple, named Timothy, whose mother was a Jewish woman who was a believer, while his father was a Greek,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}and who was well spoken of by the followers of the Lord in Lystra and Iconium.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Wishing to take this man with him on his journey, Paul caused him to be circumcised out of consideration for the Jews in that region, for they all knew that his father had been a Greek.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}As they traveled from town to town, they gave the followers the decisions which had been reached by the apostles and church elders at Jerusalem, for them to observe.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}So the churches grew stronger in the faith, and increased in numbers from day to day.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}They next went through the Phrygian district of Galatia, but were restrained by the Holy Spirit from delivering the message in Roman Asia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}When they reached the borders of Mysia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus did not permit them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Passing through Mysia, they went down to Troas;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}and there one night Paul saw a vision. A Macedonian was standing and appealing to him \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Come over to Macedonia and help us.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}So, immediately after Paul had seen the vision, we looked for an opportunity to cross over to Macedonia, concluding that God had summoned us to tell the good news to the people there.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Accordingly we set sail from Troas, and ran before the wind to Samothrace, reaching Neapolis the next day.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}From there we made our way to Philippi, which is the principal city of that part of Macedonia, and also a Roman Settlement.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
In that city we spent several days.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}On the Sabbath we went outside the gate to the riverside, where we supposed there would be a place of prayer; and we sat down and talked to the women who were gathered there.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Among them was a woman, named Lydia, belonging to Thyatira, a dealer in purple cloth, who was accustomed to join in the worship of God. The Lord touched this woman\uc1\u8217*s heart, so that she gave attention to the message delivered by Paul,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}and, when she and her household had been baptized, she urged us to become her guests.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Since you have shown your conviction,\uc1\u8217* she said, \uc1\u8216*that I really am a believer in the Lord, come and stay in my house.\uc1\u8217* And she insisted on our doing so.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}One day, as we were on our way to the place of prayer, we were met by a girl possessed by a divining spirit, who made large profits for her masters by fortune-telling.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}This girl followed Paul and the rest of us, calling, \uc1\u8216*These men are servants of the most high God, and they are bringing you news of a way to salvation.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}She had been doing this for several days, when Paul, much vexed, turned and said to the spirit within her, \uc1\u8216*In the name of Jesus Christ I command you to leave her.\uc1\u8217* That very moment the spirit left her.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}When her masters saw that there was no hope of further profit from her, they seized Paul and Silas, dragged them into the public square to the authorities,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}and took them before the Magistrates.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*These men are causing a great disturbance in our town,\uc1\u8217* they complained;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}\uc1\u8216*They are Jews, and they are teaching customs which it is not right for us, as Romans, to sanction or adopt.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}The mob rose as one person against them, and the Magistrates stripped them of their clothing and ordered them to be beaten with rods.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}After beating them severely, the Magistrates put them in prison, with orders to the jailer to keep them in safe custody.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}On receiving so strict an order, the Governor put them into the inner cell, and secured their feet in the stocks.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}About midnight, while Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and while the prisoners were listening to them,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}suddenly there was an earthquake of such violence that the jail was shaken to its foundations; all the doors flew open, and all the prisoners\uc1\u8217* chains were loosened.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}Roused from his sleep, and seeing the prison doors open, the Governor drew his sword intending to kill himself, in the belief that the prisoners had escaped.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}But Paul called our loudly, \uc1\u8216*Do not harm yourself; we are all here.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Calling for a light, the Governor rushed in, and flung himself trembling at the feet of Paul and Silas.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Then he led them out, and said, \uc1\u8216*What must I do to be saved?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}\uc1\u8216*Believe in Jesus, our Lord,\uc1\u8217* they replied, \uc1\u8216*and you will be saved, you and your household too.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}Then they spoke to him of God\uc1\u8217*s message, and to all his household as well.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}And that very hour of the night he took them and washed their wounds, and he himself and everyone belonging to him were baptized without delay.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}Afterwards he took them up to his house and set before them something to eat, rejoicing that he, with all his household, had come to believe in God.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}In the morning the Magistrates sent the guards with an order for the men to be discharged.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}The jailer told Paul of his instructions. \uc1\u8216*The Magistrates have sent an order for your discharge,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*so you had better leave the place at once and go quietly away.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}But Paul\uc1\u8217*s answer to them was, \uc1\u8216*They have flogged us in public without trial, though we are Roman citizens, and they have put us in prison, and now they are for sending us out secretly! No, indeed! Let them come and take us out themselves.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}The guards reported his words to the Magistrates, who, on hearing that Paul and Silas were Roman citizens, were alarmed,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}and went to the prison, and did their best to conciliate them. Then they took them out, and begged them to leave the city.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}When Paul and Silas left the prison, they went to Lydia\uc1\u8217*s house, and, after they had seen the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers, and encouraged them, they left the place.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 17}After passing through Amphipolis and Apollonia, Paul and Silas came to Thessalonica. Here the Jews had a synagogue;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}and, following his usual custom, Paul joined them, and for three Sabbaths addressed them, drawing his arguments from the scriptures.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}He laid before them and explained that the Christ must undergo suffering and rise from the dead; and \uc1\u8216*It is this man,\uc1\u8217* he declared, \uc1\u8216*who is the Christ \uc1\u8211* this Jesus about whom I am telling you.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Some of the people were convinced, and threw in their lot with Paul and Silas, as did also a large body of Greeks who were accustomed to join in the Jewish services, and a great number of leading women.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}But the Jewish leaders, becoming jealous, engaged some worthless fellows from the streets, and, getting a mob together, kept the city in an uproar. They attacked Jason\uc1\u8217*s house, with the intention of bringing Paul and Silas before the Popular Assembly;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}and, not finding them there, they proceeded to drag Jason and some of the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers before the city magistrates, shouting out,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*These men, who have turned the world upside down, have now come here,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}and have been harboured by Jason! They are all defying the decrees of the Emperor. They say that someone else is king \uc1\u8211* a man called Jesus!\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}On hearing this, the people and the city magistrates were much concerned;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}and, before letting them go, they took bail from Jason and the others.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}That very night the followers sent Paul and Silas off to Beroea; and on reaching that place, they went to the Jewish synagogue.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}These Jews of Beroea were better disposed than those in Thessalonica, for they welcomed the message with great readiness, and daily examined the scriptures to see if what was said was true.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}As a consequence, many of them became believers in Christ, besides a considerable number of Greek women of position, and of men also.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}But, when the Jewish leaders in Thessalonica found out that God\uc1\u8217*s message had been delivered by Paul at Beroea, they came there too, exciting and disturbing the minds of the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}The followers immediately arranged for Paul to go away to the coast, but both Silas and Timothy stayed behind in Beroea.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}The friends who escorted Paul took him as far as Athens, and, after receiving a message for Silas and Timothy to join him as quickly as possible, they started on their return.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}While Paul was waiting for them at Athens, his heart was stirred at seeing the whole city full of idols.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}So he argued in the synagogue with the Jews and with those who joined in their worship, as well as daily in the public Square with those who happened to be there.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Among others, some Epicurean and Stoic Philosophers joined issue with him. Some asked \uc1\u8216*What is this prater wanting to make out?\uc1\u8217*, while others said \uc1\u8216*He seems to be a preacher of foreign Deities.\uc1\u8217* (This was because he was telling the good news about Jesus and the resurrection).{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}So they laid hold of him and took him to the Court of Areopagus.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*May we hear,\uc1\u8217* they asked, \uc1\u8216*what new teaching this is which you are giving?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}For you are bringing some strange things to our notice, and we should like to know what they mean.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}(All Athenians and the foreigners staying in the city found no time for anything else but telling, or listening to, the last new thing.)
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}So Paul took his stand in the middle of the Court, and said \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*People of Athens, on every hand I see signs of your being very devout.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}For as I was going about, looking at your sacred shrines, I came upon an altar with this inscription \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*To an Unknown God.\uc1\u8221* What, therefore, you worship in ignorance, that I am now proclaiming to you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}The God who made the world and all things that are in it \uc1\u8211* he, Lord as he is of heaven and earth, does not live in temples made by hands,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}neither do human hands minister to his wants, as though he needed anything, since he himself gives, to all, life, and breath, and all things.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}He made all races of the earth\uc1\u8217*s surface \uc1\u8211* fixing a time for their rise and fall, and the limits of their settlements \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}That they might search for God, if by any means they might feel their way to him and find him. And yet he is not really far from any one of us;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}for in him we live and move and are. To use the words of some of your own poets \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*His offspring, too, are we.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Therefore, as the offspring of God, we must not think that the Deity has any resemblance to anything made of gold, or silver, or stone \uc1\u8211* a work of human art and imagination.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}True, God looked with indulgence on the days of people\uc1\u8217*s ignorance, but now he is announcing to everyone everywhere the need for repentance,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}because he has fixed a day on which he intends to judge the world with justice, by a man whom he has appointed \uc1\u8211* and of this he has given all people a pledge by raising this man from the dead.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}On hearing of a resurrection of the dead, some began jeering, but others said that they wanted to hear what he had to say about that another time.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}And so Paul left the Court.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}There were, however, some people who joined him, and became believers in Christ. Among them were Dionysius, a member of the Court of Areopagus, a woman named Damaris, and several others.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 18}On leaving Athens, Paul next went to Corinth.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}There he met a Jew of the name of Aquila, from Pontus, who, with his wife Priscilla, had lately come from Italy, in consequence of the order which had been issued by the Emperor Claudius for all Jews to leave Rome. Paul paid them a visit,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and, since their trade was the same as his, he stayed and worked with them \uc1\u8211* their trade was tent-making.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Every Sabbath Paul gave addresses in the synagogue, trying to convince both Jews and Greeks.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}But, when Silas and Timothy had come down from Macedonia, Paul devoted himself entirely to delivering the message, earnestly maintaining before the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}However, as they set themselves against him and became abusive, Paul shook his clothes in protest and said to them, \uc1\u8216*Your blood be on your own heads. My conscience is clear. From this time forward I will go to the Gentiles.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}So he left, and went to the house of a certain Titius Justus, who had been accustomed to join in the worship of God, and whose house was next door to the synagogue.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Crispus, the synagogue leader, came to believe in the Lord, and so did all his household; and many of the Corinthians, as they listened to Paul, became believers in Christ and were baptized.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}One night the Lord said to Paul, in a vision, \uc1\u8216*Have no fear, but continue to speak, and refuse to be silenced;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}for I am with you, and no one will do you harm, for I have many people in this city.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}So he settled there for a year and a half, and taught God\uc1\u8217*s message among the people.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}While Gallio was governor of Greece, some of the Jewish leaders made a combined attack on Paul, and brought him before the Governor\uc1\u8217*s Bench,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}charging him with persuading people to worship God in a way forbidden by the Law.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Just as Paul was on the point of speaking, Gallio said to them, \uc1\u8216*If this were a case of misdemeanour or some serious crime, there would be some reason for my listening patiently to you;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}but, since it is a dispute about words, and names, and your own Law, you must see to it yourselves. I do not choose to be a judge in such matters.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Saying this, he drove them back from the Bench.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Then they all set on Sosthenes, the synagogue leader, and beat him in front of the Bench, but Gallio did not trouble himself about any of these things.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Paul remained there some time after this, and then took leave of the followers, and sailed to Syria with Priscilla and Aquila, but not before his head had been shaved at Cenchreae, because he was under a vow.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}They put into Ephesus, and there Paul, leaving his companions, went into the synagogue and addressed the Jews.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}When they asked him to prolong his stay, he declined, saying however,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}as he took his leave, \uc1\u8216*I will come back again to you, please God,\uc1\u8217* and then set sail from Ephesus.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}On reaching Caesarea, he went up to Jerusalem and exchanged greetings with the church, and then went down to Antioch.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}After making some stay in Antioch, he set out on a tour through the Phrygian district of Galatia, strengthening the faith of all the disciples as he went.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Meanwhile there had come to Ephesus an Alexandrian Jew, named Apollos, an eloquent man, who was well-versed in the scriptures.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}He had been well-instructed in the Way of the Lord, and with burning zeal he spoke of, and taught carefully, the facts about Jesus, though he knew of no baptism but John\uc1\u8217*s.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}This man began to speak out fearlessly in the synagogue; and when Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him home and explained the Way of God to him more carefully still.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}When he wanted to cross to Greece, the followers furthered his plans, and wrote to the disciples there to welcome him. On his arrival he proved of great assistance to those who had, through the loving kindness of God, become believers in Christ,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}for he vigorously confuted the Jews, publicly proving by the scriptures that Jesus was the Christ.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 19}While Apollos was at Corinth, Paul passed through the inland districts of Roman Asia, and went to Ephesus. There he found some disciples, of whom he asked,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}\uc1\u8216*Did you, when you became believers in Christ, receive the Holy Spirit?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*No,\uc1\u8217* they answered, \uc1\u8216*we did not even hear that there was a Holy Spirit.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}\uc1\u8216*What then was your baptism?\uc1\u8217* Paul asked.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}\uc1\u8216*John\uc1\u8217*s baptism was a baptism on repentance,\uc1\u8217* rejoined Paul, \uc1\u8216*and John told the people (speaking of the \uc1\u8220*one coming\uc1\u8221* after him) that they should believe in him \uc1\u8211* that is in Jesus.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}On hearing this, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}and, after Paul had placed his hands on them, the Holy Spirit descended on them, and they began to speak in other languages and to preach.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}There were about twelve of them in all.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Paul went to the synagogue there, and for three months spoke out fearlessly, giving addresses and trying to convince his hearers, about the kingdom of God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Some of them, however, hardened their hearts and refused to believe, denouncing the Way before the people. So Paul left them and withdrew his disciples, and gave daily addresses in the lecture-hall of Tyrannus.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}This went on for two years, so that all who lived in Roman Asia, Jews and Greeks alike, heard the Lord\uc1\u8217*s message.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}God did miracles of no ordinary kind by Paul\uc1\u8217*s hands;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}so that people would carry home to the sick handkerchiefs or aprons that had touched his body, and their diseases would leave them and the wicked spirits go out of them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}An attempt was made by some itinerant Jews, who were exorcists, to use the name of the Lord Jesus over those who had wicked spirits in them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*I order you,\uc1\u8217* they would say, \uc1\u8216*by the Jesus, whom Paul preaches.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}The seven sons of Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, were doing this;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}but the wicked spirit answered them, \uc1\u8216*Jesus I acknowledge, and Paul I know, but you \uc1\u8211* who are you?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Then the man, in whom this wicked spirit was, sprang on them, mastered both of them, and so completely overpowered them, that they fled out of the house, stripped of their clothes, and wounded.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}This incident came to the knowledge of all the Jews and Greeks living at Ephesus; they were all awe-struck, and the name of the Lord Jesus was held in the highest honour.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Many, too, of those who had become believers in Christ came with a full confession of their practices;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}while a number of people, who had practiced magic, collected their books and burnt them publicly; and on reckoning up the price of these, they found it amounted to fifty thousand silver coins.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}So irresistibly did the Lord\uc1\u8217*s message spread and prevail.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Sometime after these events Paul resolved to go through Macedonia and Greece, and then make his way to Jerusalem. \uc1\u8216*And after I have been there,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*I must visit Rome also.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}So he sent to Macedonia two of his helpers, Timothy and Erastus, while he himself stayed for some time longer in Roman Asia.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Just about that time a great disturbance arose about the Way.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}A silversmith named Demetrius, who made silver models of the shrine of Artemis, and so gave a great deal of work to the artisans,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}got these men together, as well as the workmen engaged in similar occupations, and said:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Men, you know that our prosperity depends on this work,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}and you see and hear that not only at Ephesus, but in almost the whole of Roman Asia, this Paul has convinced and won over great numbers of people, by his assertion that those Gods which are made by hands are not Gods at all.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}So that not only is this business of ours likely to fall into discredit, but there is the further danger that the Temple of the great Goddess Artemis will be thought nothing of, and that she herself will be deprived of her splendour \uc1\u8211* though all Roman Asia and the whole world worship her.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}When they heard this, the men were greatly enraged, and began shouting \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}The commotion spread through the whole city, and the people rushed together into the amphitheater, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, two Macedonians who were Paul\uc1\u8217*s traveling companions.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Paul wished to go into the amphitheater and face the people, but the disciples would not let him,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}while some of the chief religious officials of the province, who were friendly to him, sent repeated entreaties to him not to trust himself inside.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}Meanwhile some were shouting one thing and some another, for the Assembly was all in confusion, most of those present not even knowing why they had met.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}But some of the crowd prompted Alexander, whom several of the Jewish leaders had pushed to the front, and he waved his hand to show that he wanted to speak in their defence to the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}However, when they recognised him as a Jew, one cry broke from them all, and they continued shouting for two hours \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}When the Recorder had succeeded in quieting the crowd, he said, \uc1\u8216*People of Ephesus, who is there, I ask you, who needs to be told that this city of Ephesus is the Warden of the Temple of the great Artemis, and of the statue which fell down from Zeus?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}As these are undeniable facts, you ought to keep calm and do nothing rash;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}for you have brought these men here, though they are neither robbers of Temples nor blasphemers of our Goddess.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}If, however, Demetrius and the artisans who are acting with him have a charge to make against anyone, there are court days and there are Magistrates; let both parties take legal proceedings.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}But if you want anything more, it will have to be settled in the regular Assembly.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}For I tell you that we are in danger of being proceeded against for today\uc1\u8217*s riot, there being nothing to account for it; and in that case we will be at a loss to give any reason for this disorderly gathering.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 41}With these words he dismissed the Assembly.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 20}When the uproar had ceased, Paul sent for the disciples, and, with encouraging words, bade them goodbye, and started on his journey to Macedonia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}After going through those districts and speaking many encouraging words to the disciples, he went into Greece, where he stayed three months.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}He was about to sail to Syria, when he learned that a plot had been laid against him by several of the Jewish leaders; so he decided to return by way of Macedonia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}He was accompanied by Sopater the son of Pyrrhus, of Beroea, Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica, Gaius of Derbe, and Timothy, as well as by Tychicus and Trophimus of Roman Asia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}These people went to Troas and waited for us there;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}while we ourselves sailed from Philippi after the Passover, and joined them five days later at Troas, where we stayed for a week.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}On the first day of the week, when we had met for the breaking of bread, Paul, who was intending to leave the next day, began to address those who were present, and prolonged his address until midnight.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}There were a good many lamps in the upstairs room, where we had met;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}and a young man named Eutychus, sitting at the window, was gradually overcome with great drowsiness, as Paul continued his address. At last, quite overpowered by his drowsiness, he fell from the third story to the ground, and was picked up for dead.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}But Paul went down, threw himself on him, and put his arms round him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Do not be alarmed,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*he is still alive.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then he went upstairs; and, after breaking and partaking of the bread, he talked with them at great length until daybreak, and then left.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Meanwhile they had taken the lad away alive, and were greatly comforted.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}We started first, went on board ship, and sailed for Assos, intending to take Paul on board there. This was by his own arrangement, as he intended to go by land himself.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}So, when he met us at Assos, we took him on board and went on to Mitylene.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}The day after we had sailed from there, we arrived off Chios, touched at Samos the following day, and the next day reached Miletus;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}for Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus, so as to avoid spending much time in Roman Asia. He was making haste to reach Jerusalem, if possible, by the Festival at the close of the Harvest.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}From Miletus, however, he sent to Ephesus and invited the church elders to meet him;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and, when they came, he said to them, \uc1\u8216*You know well the life that I always led among you from the very first day that I set foot in Roman Asia,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}serving the Lord, as I did, in all humility, amid the tears and trials which fell to my lot through the plots of some of the Jewish leaders.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}I never shrank from telling you anything that could be helpful to you, or from teaching you both in public and in private.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}I earnestly pointed both Jews and Greeks to the repentance that leads to God, and to faith in Jesus, our Lord.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}And now, under spiritual constraint, I am here on my way to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}except that in town after town the Holy Spirit plainly declares to me that imprisonment and troubles await me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}But I count my life of no value to myself, if only I may complete the course marked out for me, and the task that was allotted me by the Lord Jesus \uc1\u8211* which was to declare the good news of the love of God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And now, I tell you, I know that none of you will ever see my face again \uc1\u8211* you among whom I have gone about proclaiming the kingdom.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Therefore I declare to you this day, that my conscience is clear in regard to the fate of any of you,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}for I have not shrunk from announcing the whole purpose of God regarding you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Be watchful over yourselves, and over the whole flock, of which the Holy Spirit has placed you in charge, to shepherd the church of God, which he won for himself at the cost of his life.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}I know that, after my departure, merciless wolves will get in among you, who will not spare the flock;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}and from among yourselves, too, people will arise, who will teach perversions of truth, so as to draw away the disciples after them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}Therefore, be on your guard, remembering how for three years, night and day, I never ceased, even with tears, to warn each one of you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And now I commend you to the Lord and to the message of his love \uc1\u8211* a message which has the power to build up your characters, and to give you your place among all those who have become Christ\uc1\u8217*s people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}I have never coveted anyone\uc1\u8217*s gold or silver or clothing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}You, yourselves, know that these hands of mine provided not only for my own wants, but for my companions also.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}I left nothing undone to show you that, labouring as I laboured, you ought to help the weak, and to remember the words of the Lord Jesus, how he said himself \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*It is more blessed to give than to receive.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}When Paul had finished speaking, he knelt down and prayed with them all.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}All were in tears; and throwing their arms round Paul\uc1\u8217*s neck, they kissed him again and again,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}grieving most of all over what he had said \uc1\u8211* that they would never see his face again. Then they escorted him to the ship.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 21}When we had torn ourselves away and had set sail, we ran before the wind to Cos; the next day we came to Rhodes, and from there to Patara,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}where we found a ship crossing to Phoenicia, and went on board and set sail.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}After sighting Cyprus and leaving it on the left, we sailed to Syria, and put into Tyre, where the ship was to discharge her cargo.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}There we found the disciples and stayed a week with them. Speaking under the influence of the Spirit, they warned Paul not to set foot in Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}However, when we had come to the end of our visit, we went on our way, all the disciples with their wives and children escorting us out of the city. We knelt down on the beach, and prayed,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}and then said goodbye to one another; after which we went on board, and they returned home.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}After we had made the run from Tyre, we landed at Ptolemais, and exchanged greetings with the followers there, and spent a day with them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}The next day we left, and reached Caesarea, where we went to the house of Philip, the missionary, who was one of the Seven, and stayed with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}He had four unmarried daughters, who had the gift of prophecy.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}During our visit, which lasted several days, a prophet, named Agabus, came down from Judea.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}He came to see us, and, taking Paul\uc1\u8217*s belt, and binding his own feet and hands with it, said, \uc1\u8216*This is what the Holy Spirit says \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*The man to whom this belt belongs will be bound like this by the religious authorities in Jerusalem, and they will give him up to the Gentiles\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}When we heard that, we and the people of the place began to entreat Paul not to go up to Jerusalem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}It was then that Paul made the reply, \uc1\u8216*Why are you weeping and breaking my heart like this? For my part, I am ready not only to be bound, but even to suffer death at Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}So, as he would not be persuaded, we said no more to him, only adding \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*The Lord\uc1\u8217*s will be done.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}At the end of our visit, we made our preparations, and started on our way up to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Some of the disciples from Caesarea went with us, and brought Mnason with them, a Cypriot disciple of long standing, with whom we were to stay.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}On our arrival at Jerusalem, the followers of the Lord there gave us a hearty welcome;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and the next day Paul went with us to see James, and all the church elders were present.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}After greeting them, Paul related in detail all that God had done among the Gentiles through his efforts;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}and, when they had heard it, they began praising God, and said to Paul:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*You see, brother, that those of our people who have become believers in Christ may be numbered by tens of thousands, and they are all naturally earnest in upholding the Jewish Law.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Now they have heard it said about you, that you teach all of our people in foreign countries to forsake Moses, for you tell them not to circumcise their children or even to observe Jewish customs.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Well now, as they are certain to hear of your arrival, do what we are going to suggest.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}We have four men here, who have of their own accord put themselves under a vow.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Join these men, share their purification, and bear their expenses, so that they may shave their heads; and then all will see that there is no truth in what they have been told about you, but that, on the contrary, you yourself rule your life in obedience to the Jewish Law.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}As to the Gentiles who have become believers in Christ, we have sent our decision that they should avoid food offered to idols, and blood, and the flesh of strangled animals, and impurity.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Paul joined the men, and the next day shared their purification, and went into the Temple, and gave notice of the expiration of the period of purification when the usual offering should have been made on behalf of each of them.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}But, just as the seven days were drawing to a close, some of the Jewish people from Roman Asia caught sight of Paul in the Temple, and caused great excitement among all the people present, by seizing Paul and shouting,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}\uc1\u8216*People of Israel! Help! This is the man who teaches everyone everywhere against our people, our Law, and this place; and, what is more, he has actually brought Greeks into the Temple and defiled this sacred place.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}(For they had previously seen Trophimus the Ephesian in Paul\uc1\u8217*s company in the city, and were under the belief that Paul had taken him into the Temple.)
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}The whole city was stirred, and the people quickly collected, seized Paul, and dragged him out of the Temple, when the doors were immediately shut.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}They were bent on killing him, when it was reported to the officer commanding the garrison, that all Jerusalem was in commotion.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}He instantly got together some officers and soldiers, and charged down on the crowd, who, when they saw the commanding officer and his soldiers, stopped beating Paul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}Then he went up to Paul, arrested him, ordered him to be doubly chained, and proceeded to inquire who he was, and what he had been doing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}Some of the crowd said one thing, and some another; and, as he could get no definite reply because of the uproar, he ordered Paul to be taken into the barracks.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}When Paul reached the steps, he was actually being carried by the soldiers, owing to the violence of the mob;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}for the people were following in a mass, shouting out, \uc1\u8216*Kill him!\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}Just as he was about to be taken into the Fort, Paul said to the commanding officer, \uc1\u8216*May I speak to you?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Do you know Greek?\uc1\u8217* asked the commanding officer.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}\uc1\u8216*Aren\uc1\u8217*t you, then, the Egyptian who some time ago raised an insurrection and led the four thousand Bandits out into the wilderness?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}\uc1\u8216*No,\uc1\u8217* said Paul, \uc1\u8216*I am a Jew of Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of a city of some note. I beg you to give me permission to speak to the people.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}The commanding officer gave his permission, and Paul, standing on the steps, made signs with his hand to the people, and, when comparative silence had been obtained, he said to them in Hebrew:{\cf1\f1\fs22 22}\uc1\u8216*Brothers and fathers, listen to the defence which I am about to make.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}When they heard that he was speaking to them in Hebrew, they were still more quiet; and Paul went on:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}\uc1\u8216*I am a Jew, from Tarsus in Cilicia, but I was brought up in this city under the teaching of Gamaliel, and educated in accordance with the strict system of our ancestral Law. I was as zealous in God\uc1\u8217*s service as any of you who are here today.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}In my persecution of this Way I did not stop even at the taking of life. I put in chains, and imprisoned, men and women alike \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And to that the high priest himself and all the council of elders can testify. For I had letters of introduction from them to our fellow Jews at Damascus, and I was on my way to that place, to bring those whom I might find there prisoners to Jerusalem for punishment.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}While I was still on my way, just as I was getting close to Damascus, about midday, suddenly there flashed from the heavens a great light all round me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}I fell to the ground, and heard a voice saying to me \uc1\u8220*Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}\uc1\u8220*Who are you, Lord?\uc1\u8221* I replied. Then the voice said \uc1\u8220*I am Jesus of Nazareth whom you are persecuting.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}The men with me saw the light, but did not hear the speaker\uc1\u8217*s voice.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Then I said \uc1\u8220*What am I to do, Lord?\uc1\u8221* \uc1\u8220*Get up and go into Damascus,\uc1\u8221* The Lord said to me, \uc1\u8220*and there you will be told all that you have been appointed to do.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}In consequence of that dazzling light I could not see, but my companions held me by the hand, until I reached Damascus.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}There a man named Ananias, a strict observer of our Law, well spoken of by all the Jewish inhabitants, came to see me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Standing close to me, he said \uc1\u8220*Saul, my brother, recover your sight.\uc1\u8221* And then and there I recovered my sight and looked up at him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Then he said \uc1\u8220*The God of our ancestors has appointed you to learn his will, and to see the righteous one, and to hear words from his lips;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}for you will be a witness for him to all the world of what you have just seen and heard.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}And now why wait any longer, Be baptized at once, wash away your sins, and invoke his name.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}After my return to Jerusalem, while I was praying one day in the Temple, I fell into a trance,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and saw Jesus saying to me \uc1\u8220*Make haste and leave Jerusalem at once, because they will not accept your testimony about me.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}\uc1\u8220*Lord,\uc1\u8221* I answered, \uc1\u8220*these people know that I used to imprison and scourge, in synagogue after synagogue, those who believed in you;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}and, when the blood of your martyr, Stephen, was being shed, I was myself standing by, approving of his death, and took charge of the clothes of those who were murdering him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}But Jesus said to me \uc1\u8220*Go; for I will send you to the Gentiles far away\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Up to this point the people had been listening to Paul, but at these words they called out, \uc1\u8216*Kill him! A fellow like this ought not to have been allowed to live!\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}As they were shouting, tearing off their clothes, and throwing dust in the air,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}the commanding officer ordered Paul to be taken into the Fort, and directed that he should be examined under the lash so that he might find out the reason for their outcry against him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}But just as they had tied him up to be scourged, Paul said to the centurion standing near, \uc1\u8216*Is it legal for you to scourge a Roman citizen, unconvicted?\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}On hearing this, the centurion went and reported it to the commanding officer. \uc1\u8216*Do you know what you are doing?\uc1\u8217* he said. \uc1\u8216*This man is a Roman citizen.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}So the commanding officer went up to Paul and said, \uc1\u8216*Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Yes,\uc1\u8217* replied Paul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}\uc1\u8216*I had to pay a heavy price for my position as citizen,\uc1\u8217* said the officer. \uc1\u8216*I am one by birth,\uc1\u8217* rejoined Paul.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}The men who were to have examined Paul immediately drew back, and the officer, finding that Paul was a Roman citizen, was alarmed at having put him in chains.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}On the next day the commanding officer, wishing to find out the real reason why Paul was denounced by the Jewish leaders, had his chains taken off, and directed the chief priests and the whole of the High Council to assemble, and then took Paul down and brought him before them.{\cf1\f1\fs22 23}Paul fixed his eyes on the Council, and began:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Brothers, for my part, I have always ordered my life before God, with a clear conscience, up to this very day.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}At this, the high priest Ananias ordered the men standing near to strike him on the mouth;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Paul turned to him and said:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*God will strike you, you whitewashed wall! Are you sitting there to try me in accordance with law, and yet, in defiance of law, order me to be struck?\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}The people standing near said to Paul, \uc1\u8216*Do you know that you are insulting God\uc1\u8217*s high priest?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}\uc1\u8216*I did not know, brothers, that it was the high priest,\uc1\u8217* said Paul, \uc1\u8216*for scripture says \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
\uc1\u8220*Of the ruler of your people you should speak no ill\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Noticing that some of those present were Sadducees and others Pharisees, Paul called out in the Council, \uc1\u8216*Brothers, I am a Pharisee and a son of Pharisees. It is on the question of hope for the dead and of their resurrection that I am on my trial.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}As soon as he said this, a dispute arose between the Pharisees and the Sadducees; and there was a sharp division of opinion among those present.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}(For Sadducees say there is no such thing as a resurrection, and that there is neither angel nor spirit, while Pharisees believe in both.){\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}So a great uproar ensued, and some of the Teachers of the Law belonging to the Pharisees\uc1\u8217* party stood up and hotly protested, \uc1\u8216*We find nothing whatever wrong in this man. Suppose a spirit did speak to him, or an angel\uc1\u8230*\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}The dispute was becoming so violent, that the commanding officer, fearing that Paul would be torn in pieces between them, ordered the Guard to go down and rescue him from them, and take him into the Fort.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}That night the Lord came and stood by Paul, and said, \uc1\u8216*Courage! You have borne witness for me in Jerusalem and you must bear witness in Rome also.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}In the morning some Jewish men combined together, and took an oath that they would not eat or drink until they had killed Paul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}There were more than forty in the plot;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}and they went to the chief priests and the elders, and said, \uc1\u8216*We have taken a solemn oath not to touch food until we have killed Paul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}So we want you now, with the consent of the Council, to suggest to the commanding officer that he should bring Paul down before you, as though you intended to go more fully into his case; but, before he comes here, we will be ready to make away with him.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}However, the son of Paul\uc1\u8217*s sister, hearing of the plot, went to the Fort, and on being admitted, told Paul about it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Paul called one of the garrison centurion and asked him to take the lad to the commanding officer, as he had something to tell him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}The centurion went with the lad to the commanding officer, and said, \uc1\u8216*The prisoner Paul called me and asked me to bring this lad to you, as he has something to tell you.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}The commanding officer took the lad by the hand, and, stepping aside, asked what it was he had to tell him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}\uc1\u8216*Some men have agreed,\uc1\u8217* answered the lad, \uc1\u8216*to ask you to bring Paul down before the Council tomorrow, on the plea of your making further inquiry into his case.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}But do not let them persuade you, for more than forty of them are lying in wait for him, who have taken an oath that they will not eat or drink, until they have made away with him; and they are at this very moment in readiness, counting on your promise.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}The commanding officer then dismissed the lad, cautioning him not to mention to anybody that he had given him that information.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Then he called two Captains, and ordered them to have two hundred soldiers ready to go to Caesarea, as well as seventy troopers and two hundred lancers, by nine o\uc1\u8217*clock that night,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}and to have horses ready for Paul to ride, so that they might take him safely to Felix, the Governor.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}He also wrote a letter along these lines:
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}\uc1\u8220*Claudius Lysias sends his compliments to His Excellency Felix the Governor.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}The man whom I send with this had been seized by some Jews, and was on the point of being killed by them, when I came upon them with the force under my command, and rescued him, as I learned that he was a Roman citizen.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Wanting to know exactly the ground of the charges they made against him, I brought him before their Council,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}when I found that their charges were connected with questions of their own Law, and that there was nothing alleged involving either death or imprisonment.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Having, however, information of a plot against the man, which was about to be put into execution, I am sending him to you at once, and I have also directed his accusers to prosecute him before you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}The soldiers, in accordance with their orders, took charge of Paul and conducted him by night to Antipatris;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}and on the next day, leaving the troopers to go on with him, they returned to the Fort.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}On arriving at Caesarea, the troopers delivered the letter to the Governor, and brought Paul before him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}As soon as Felix had read the letter, he enquired to what province Paul belonged, and, learning that he came from Cilicia, he said,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}\uc1\u8216*I will hear all you have to say as soon as your accusers have arrived.\uc1\u8217* And he ordered Paul to be kept under guard in Herod\uc1\u8217*s Government house.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 24}Five days afterwards the high priest Ananias came down with some of the elders and a barrister named Tertullus. They laid an information with the Governor against Paul;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}and, when the hearing came on, Tertullus began his speech for the prosecution.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}\uc1\u8216*We owe it to your Excellency,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*that we are enjoying profound peace, and we owe it to your foresight that this nation is constantly securing reforms \uc1\u8211* advantages which we very gratefully accept at all times and places.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}But \uc1\u8211* not to be tedious \uc1\u8211* I beg you, with your accustomed fairness, to listen to a brief statement of our case.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}We have found this man a public pest; he is one who stirs up disputes among our people all the world over, and is a ringleader of the Nazarene heretics.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}He even attempted to desecrate the Temple itself, but we caught him;{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}  Some later manuscripts add: We wanted to judge him according to our law. But Lysias the commanding officer came and took him out of our hands by force, ordering his accusers to come before you. }{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}and you will be able, by examining him on all these points, to satisfy yourself as to the charges which we are bringing against him.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}The Jewish crowd also joined in the attack and bore out his statements.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}On a sign from the Governor, Paul made this reply:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*Knowing, as I do, for how many years you have acted as judge to this nation, it is with confidence that I undertake my own defence.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}For you can easily verify that it is not more than twelve days ago that I went up to worship at Jerusalem,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}where my prosecutors never found me holding discussions with anyone, or causing a crowd to collect \uc1\u8211* either in the Temple, or in the synagogues, or about the city;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}and they cannot establish the charges which they are now making against me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}This, however, I do acknowledge to you, that it is as a believer in the Way which they call heretical, that I worship the God of my ancestors. At the same time, I believe everything that is in accordance with the Law and that is written in the prophets;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}and I have a hope that rests in God \uc1\u8211* a hope which they also cherish \uc1\u8211* that there will one day be a resurrection of good and bad alike.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}This being so, I strive at all times to keep my conscience clear before both God and people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}After some years\uc1\u8217* absence I had come to bring charitable gifts to my nation, and to make offerings;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and it was while engaged in this that they found me in the Temple, after completing a period of purification, but not with any crowd or disorder.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}There were, however, some Jews from Roman Asia who ought to have been here before you, and to have made any charge that they may have against me \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Or else let my opponents here say what they found wrong in me when I was before the Council,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}except as to the one sentence that I shouted out as I stood among them \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*It is about the resurrection of the dead that I am on my trial before you today\uc1\u8221*.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Felix, however, adjourned the case \uc1\u8211* though he had a fairly accurate knowledge of all that concerned the Way \uc1\u8211* with the promise, \uc1\u8216*When Lysias, the commanding officer, comes down, I will give my decision in your case.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}So he gave orders to the centurion in charge of Paul to keep him in custody, but to relax the regulations, and not to prevent any of his personal friends from attending to his wants.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Some days later Felix came with his wife Drusilla, who was Jewish, and, sending for Paul, listened to what he had to say about faith in Christ Jesus.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}But, while Paul was speaking at length about righteousness, self-control, and the coming judgment, Felix became terrified, and interrupted him \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8216*Go for the present, but, when I find an opportunity, I will send for you again.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}He was hoping, too, for a bribe from Paul, and so he used to send for him frequently and talk with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}But, after the lapse of two years, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus; and, wishing to gain popularity with the Jewish leaders, he left Paul a prisoner.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 25}Three days after Festus had arrived in his province, he left Caesarea and went up to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}There the chief priests and the leading men among the Jews laid an information before him against Paul,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and asked a favour of him, to Paul\uc1\u8217*s injury \uc1\u8211* to have Paul brought to Jerusalem. All the while they were plotting to make away with him on the road.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}But Festus answered that Paul was in prison at Caesarea, and that he himself would be leaving for that place shortly.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}\uc1\u8216*So let the influential men among you,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*go down with me, and if there is anything amiss in the man, charge him formally with it.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}After staying among them some eight or ten days, Festus went down to Caesarea. The next day he took his seat on the Bench, and ordered Paul to be brought before him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}On Paul\uc1\u8217*s appearance, the Jewish leaders who had come down from Jerusalem surrounded him, and made many serious charges, which they failed to establish.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Paul\uc1\u8217*s answer to the charge was \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*I have not committed any offence against the Jewish Law, or the Temple, or the Emperor.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}But, as Festus wished to gain popularity with the Jews, he interrupted Paul with the question, \uc1\u8216*Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem and be tried on these charges before me there?\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}\uc1\u8216*No,\uc1\u8217* replied Paul, \uc1\u8216*I am standing at the Emperor\uc1\u8217*s court, where I ought to be tried. I have not wronged the Jews, as you yourself are well aware.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}If, however, I am breaking the law and have committed any offence deserving death, I do not ask to escape the penalty; but, if there is nothing in the accusations of these people, no one has the power to give me up to them. I appeal to the Emperor.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Festus, after conferring with his Council, answered, \uc1\u8216*You have appealed to the Emperor; to the Emperor you will go.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Some days later King Agrippa and Bernice came down to Caesarea, and paid a visit of congratulation to Festus;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}and, as they were staying there for several days, Festus laid Paul\uc1\u8217*s case before the king. \uc1\u8216*There is a man here,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*left a prisoner by Felix,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}about whom, when I came to Jerusalem, the Jewish chief priest and the elders laid an information, demanding judgment against him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}My answer to them was, that it was not the practice of Romans to give up anyone to their accusers until the accused had met them face to face, and had also had an opportunity of answering the charges brought against them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}So they met here, and without loss of time I took my seat on the Bench the very next day, and ordered the man to be brought before me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}But, when his accusers came forward, they brought no charge of wrongdoing such as I had expected;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}but I found that there were certain questions in dispute between them about their own religion, and about some dead man called Jesus, whom Paul declared to be alive.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And, as I was at a loss how to enquire into questions of this kind, I asked Paul if he were willing to go up to Jerusalem, and be put on trial there.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Paul, however, appealed to have his case reserved for the consideration of his August Majesty, so I ordered him to be detained in custody, until I could send him to the Emperor.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}\uc1\u8216*I should like to hear this man myself,\uc1\u8217* Agrippa said to Festus.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*You will hear him tomorrow,\uc1\u8217* Festus answered.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}So the next day, when Agrippa and Bernice had come in full state and had entered the Audience Chamber, with the superior officers and the principal people of the city, by the order of Festus Paul was brought before them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Then Festus said, \uc1\u8216*King Agrippa, and all here present, you see before you the man about whom the whole Jewish people have applied to me, both at Jerusalem and here, loudly asserting that he ought not to be allowed to live.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}I found, however, that he had not done anything deserving death; so, as he had himself appealed to his August Majesty, I decided to send him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}But I have nothing definite to write about him to my Imperial Master; and for that reason I have brought him before you all, and especially before you, King Agrippa, that, after examining him, I may have something to write.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}For it seems to me absurd to send a prisoner, without at the same time stating the charges made against him.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 26}Turning to Paul, Agrippa said, \uc1\u8216*You are at liberty to speak for yourself.\uc1\u8217* Then Paul stretched out his hand and began his defence.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}\uc1\u8216*I have been congratulating myself, King Agrippa,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*that it is before you that I have to make my defence today, with regard to all the charges brought against me by my own people,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}especially as you are so well-versed in all the customs and questions of the Jewish world. I beg you therefore to give me a patient hearing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}My life, then, from youth upwards, was passed, from the very first, among my own nation, and in Jerusalem, and is within the knowledge of all Jews;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}and they have always known \uc1\u8211* if they choose to give evidence \uc1\u8211* that, in accordance with the very strictest form of our religion, I lived a true Pharisee.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Even now, it is because of my hope in the promise given by God to our ancestors that I stand here on my trial \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}A promise which our twelve tribes, by earnest service night and day, hope to see fulfilled. It is for this hope, your Majesty, that I am accused \uc1\u8211* and by Jews themselves!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Why do you all hold it incredible that God should raise the dead?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}I myself, it is true, once thought it my duty to oppose in every way the name of Jesus of Nazareth;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}and I actually did so at Jerusalem. Acting on the authority of the chief priests, I myself threw many of the people of Christ into prison, and, when it was proposed to put them to death, I gave my vote for it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Time after time, in every synagogue, I tried by punishments to force them to blaspheme. So frantic was I against them, that I pursued them even to towns beyond our borders.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}It was while I was traveling to Damascus on an errand of this kind, entrusted with full powers by the chief priests,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}that at midday, your Majesty, I saw right in my path, coming from the heavens, a light brighter than the glare of the sun, which shone all round me and those traveling with me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}We all fell to the ground, and then I heard a voice saying to me in Hebrew \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? By kicking against the goad you are punishing yourself.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}\uc1\u8220*Who are you, Lord?\uc1\u8221* I asked. And the Lord said, \uc1\u8220*I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}but get up and stand upright; for I have appeared to you in order to appoint you a servant and a witness of those revelations of me which you have already had, and of those in which I will yet appear to you,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}since I am choosing you out from your own people and from the Gentiles, to whom I now send you,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}to open their eyes, and to turn them from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan to God; so that they may receive pardon for their sins, and a place among those who have become God\uc1\u8217*s people, by faith in me.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}After that, King Agrippa, I did not fail to obey the heavenly vision;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}on the contrary, first to those at Damascus and Jerusalem, and then through the whole of Judea, and to the Gentiles as well, I began to preach repentance and conversion to God, and a life befitting that repentance.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}This is why some men seized me in the Temple, and made attempts on my life.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}However I have received help from God to this very day, and so stand here, and bear my testimony to high and low alike \uc1\u8211* without adding a word to what the prophets, as well as Moses, declared should happen \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}That the Christ must suffer, and that, by rising from the dead, he was destined to be the first to bring news of light, not only to our nation, but also to the Gentiles.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}While Paul was making this defence, Festus called out loudly, \uc1\u8216*You are mad, Paul; your great learning is driving you mad.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}\uc1\u8216*I am not mad, your Excellency,\uc1\u8217* he replied. \uc1\u8216*On the contrary, the statements that I am making are true and sober.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Indeed, the king knows about these matters, so I speak before him without constraint. I am sure that there is nothing whatever of what I have been telling him that has escaped his attention; for all this has not been done in a corner.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know you do.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}But Agrippa said to Paul, \uc1\u8216*You are soon trying to make a Christian of me!\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}\uc1\u8216*Whether it is soon or late,\uc1\u8217* answered Paul, \uc1\u8216*I pray to God that not only you, but all who are listening to me, might today become just what I am myself \uc1\u8211* except for these chains!\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Then the king rose, with the Governor and Bernice and those who had been sitting with them,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}and, after retiring, discussed the case among themselves. \uc1\u8216*There is nothing,\uc1\u8217* they said, \uc1\u8216*deserving death or imprisonment in this man\uc1\u8217*s conduct\uc1\u8217*;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}and, speaking to Festus, Agrippa added, \uc1\u8216*The man might have been discharged, if he had not appealed to the Emperor.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 27}As it was decided that we were to sail to Italy, Paul and some other prisoners were put in charge of a centurion of the Augustan Guard, named Julius.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}We went on board a ship from Adramyttium, which was on the point of sailing to the ports along the coast of Roman Asia, and put to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian from Thessalonica, went with us.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}The next day we put in to Sidon, where Julius treated Paul in a friendly manner, and allowed him to go to see his friends and receive their hospitality.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Putting to sea again, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the wind was against us;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}and, after crossing the sea of Cilicia and Pamphylia, we reached Myra in Lycia.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}There the Roman officer found an Alexandrian ship on her way to Italy, and put us on board of her.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}For several days our progress was slow, and it was only with difficulty that we arrived off Cnidus. As the wind was still unfavourable when we came off Cape Salmone, we sailed under the lee of Crete,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}and with difficulty, by keeping close in shore, we reached a place called \uc1\u8220*Fair Havens,\uc1\u8221* near which was the town of Lasea.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}This had taken a considerable time, and sailing was already dangerous, for the Fast was already over; and so Paul gave this warning.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}\uc1\u8216*My friends,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*I see that this voyage will be attended with injury and much damage, not only to the cargo and the ship, but to our own lives also.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}The Roman officer, however, was more influenced by the captain and the owner than by what was said by Paul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And, as the harbour was not a suitable one to winter in, the majority were in favour of continuing the voyage, in hope of being able to reach Phoenix, and winter there. Phoenix was a Cretan harbour, open to the north-east and south-east.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}So, when a light wind sprang up from the south, thinking that they had found their opportunity, they weighed anchor and kept along the coast of Crete, close in shore.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}But shortly afterwards a hurricane came down on us off the land \uc1\u8211* a north-easter, as it is called.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}The ship was caught by it and was unable to keep her head to the wind, so we had to give way and let her drive before it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Running under the lee of a small island called Cauda, we only just managed to secure the ship\uc1\u8217*s boat,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}and, after hoisting it on board, the men frapped the ship. But, afraid of being driven on to the Syrtis Sands, they lowered the yard, and then drifted.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}So violently were we tossed about by the storm, that the next day they began throwing the cargo overboard,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}and, on the following day, threw out the ship\uc1\u8217*s tackle with their own hands.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}As neither sun nor stars were visible for several days, and, as the gale still continued severe, all hope of our being saved was at last abandoned.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}It was then, when they had gone a long time without food, that Paul came forward, and said, \uc1\u8216*My friends, you should have listened to me, and not have sailed from Crete and so incurred this injury and damage.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Yet, even as things are, I beg you not to lose courage, for there will not be a single life lost among you \uc1\u8211* only the ship.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}For last night an angel of the God to whom I belong, and whom I serve, stood by me, and said \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}\uc1\u8220*Have no fear, Paul; you must appear before the Emperor, and God himself has given you the lives of all your fellow voyagers.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Therefore, courage, my friends! For I believe God, that everything will happen exactly as I have been told.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}We will, however, have to be driven on some island.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}It was now the fourteenth night of the storm, and we were drifting about in the Adriatic Sea, when, about midnight, the sailors began to suspect that they were drawing near land.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}So they took soundings, and found twenty fathoms of water. After waiting a little, they took soundings again, and found fifteen fathoms.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Then, as they were afraid of our being driven on some rocky coast, they let go four anchors from the stern, and longed for daylight.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}The sailors wanted to leave the ship, and had lowered the boat, on pretence of running out anchors from the bows,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}when Paul said to the Roman officer and his men, \uc1\u8216*Unless the sailors remain on board, you cannot be saved.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}So the soldiers cut the ropes which held the boat, and let her drift away.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}In the interval before daybreak Paul kept urging them all to take something to eat.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*It is a fortnight today,\uc1\u8217* he said, \uc1\u8216*that, owing to your anxiety, you have gone without food, taking nothing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}So I beg you to take something to eat; your safety depends on it, for not one of you will lose even a hair of his head.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}With these words he took some bread, and, after saying the thanksgiving to God before them all, broke it in pieces, and began to eat;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}and the men all felt cheered and had something to eat themselves.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}There were about seventy-six of us on board, all told.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}After satisfying their hunger, they further lightened the ship by throwing the grain into the sea.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}When daylight came, they could not make out what land it was, but, observing a creek in which there was a beach, they consulted as to whether they could run the ship safely into it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}Then they cast off, and abandoned the anchors, and at the same time unlashed the gear of the steering oars, hoisted the foresail to the wind, and made for the beach.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 41}They got, however, into a kind of channel, and there ran the ship aground. The bows stuck fast and could not be moved, while the stern began breaking up under the strain.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 42}The advice of the soldiers was that the prisoners should be killed, so that none of them could swim away and make their escape.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 43}But the Roman officer, anxious to save Paul, prevented their carrying out their intention, and ordered that those who could swim should be the first to jump into the sea and try to reach the shore;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 44}and that the rest should follow, some on planks, and others on different pieces of the ship. In these various ways everyone managed to get safely ashore.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 28}When we were all safe, we found that the island was called Malta.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}The island\uc1\u8217*s people showed us marked kindness, for they lit a fire and took us all under shelter, because it had come on to rain and was cold.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Paul had gathered a quantity of dry sticks and laid them on the fire, when a poisonous snake, driven out by the heat, fastened on his hand.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}When the islanders saw the creature hanging from his hand, they said to one another, \uc1\u8216*Evidently this man is a murderer, for though he has been saved from the sea, Justice has not allowed him to live.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}However, Paul shook the creature off into the fire and took no harm.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}The islanders were expecting inflammation to set in, or that he would suddenly fall dead; but, after waiting for a long time, and seeing that there was nothing amiss with him, they changed their minds and said that he was a God.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}In that region there was an estate belonging to the Governor of the island, whose name was Publius. He took us up to his house, and for three days entertained us most courteously.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}It happened that the father of Publius was lying ill of fever and dysentery. So Paul went to see him; and, after praying, he placed his hands on him and cured him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}After this, all the people in the island who had any illness came to Paul, and were cured.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}They also presented us with many gifts, and when we set sail they put supplies of necessaries on board.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}After three months, we set sail in a ship that had wintered in the island. She was an Alexandrian vessel, and had the Twin sons of Zeus for her figure-head.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}We put in at Syracuse and stayed there three days,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}and from there we worked to windward and so got to Rhegium. A day later a south wind sprang up and took us to Puteoli in two days.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}There we found some of the Lord\uc1\u8217*s followers, and were urged to stay a week with them; after which we went on to Rome.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}The followers there had heard about us, and came out as far as the Market of Appius and the Three Taverns to meet us. At sight of them Paul thanked God and was much cheered.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}On our reaching Rome, Paul was allowed to live by himself, except for the soldier who was in charge of him.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Three days after our arrival, Paul invited the leading Jews to meet him; and, when they came, he said, \uc1\u8216*Brothers, although I had done nothing hostile to the interests of our nation or to our ancestral customs, yet I was sent from Jerusalem as a prisoner, and handed over to the Romans.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}The Romans, when they had examined me, were ready to release me, because there was nothing in my conduct deserving death.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}But, as the Jewish leaders opposed my release, I was compelled to appeal to the Emperor \uc1\u8211* not, indeed, that I had any charge to make against my own nation.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}This, then, is my reason for urging you to come to see me and talk with me; because it is for the sake of the hope of Israel that I am here in chains.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}\uc1\u8216*We,\uc1\u8217* was their reply, \uc1\u8216*have not had any letter about you from Judea, nor have any of our fellow Jews come and reported or said anything bad about you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}But we will be glad to hear from you what your views are, for, with regard to this sect, we are well aware that it is spoken against on all sides.\uc1\u8217*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}They then fixed a day with him, and came to the place where he was staying, in even larger numbers, when Paul proceeded to lay the subject before them. He bore his testimony to the kingdom of God, and tried to convince them about Jesus, by arguments drawn from the Law of Moses and from the prophets \uc1\u8211* speaking from morning until evening.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Some were inclined to accept what he said; others, however, rejected it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}So, as they disagreed among themselves, they began to disperse, Paul adding only \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
\uc1\u8216*True, indeed, was the declaration made by the Holy Spirit, through the prophet Isaiah to your ancestors \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Go to this nation and say:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
You will hear with your ears without ever understanding,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-1720\li2800
and, though you have eyes, you will see without ever perceiving.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}For the mind of this nation has grown dense,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-1720\li2800
and their ears are dull of hearing,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-1720\li2800
their eyes also have they closed;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
otherwise some day they might see with their eyes,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
and with their ears they might hear,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
and in their mind they might understand, and might turn \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-1720\li2800
and I might heal them.
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi0 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Understand, then, that this salvation of God was sent for the Gentiles; and they will listen.\uc1\u8217*{\super\chftn}{\footnote\pard\plain\chftn {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}  Some later manuscripts add: After he said these things the Jews left, all the while engaging in a heated debate among themselves. }
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}For two whole years Paul stayed in a house which he rented for himself, welcoming all who came to see him,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}proclaiming the kingdom of God, and teaching about the Lord Jesus Christ, with perfect fearlessness, unhindered.
\par}
\sectd\sect{\header \pard\qr\plain\f0\fs16 Romans (Page \chpgn) \par}{\pard \pagebb
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs56 Paul\uc1\u8217*s Letter to the

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs72 Romans

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs32 Introduction

\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 1}From Paul, a servant of Jesus Christ, who has been called to become an apostle, and has been set apart to tell God\uc1\u8217*s good news.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}This good news God promised long ago through his prophets in the sacred scriptures,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}concerning his Son, Jesus Christ, our Lord; who, as to his human nature, was descended from David,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}but, as to the spirit of holiness within him, was miraculously designated Son of God by his resurrection from the dead.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Through him we received the gift of the apostolic office, to win submission to the faith among all nations for the glory of his name.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And among these nations are you \uc1\u8211* you who have been called to belong to Jesus Christ.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}To all in Rome who are dear to God and have been called to become Christ\uc1\u8217*s people, may God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ bless you and give you peace.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for you all, because the report of your faith is spreading throughout the world.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}God, to whom I offer the worship of my soul as I tell the goodness of his Son, is my witness how constantly I mention you when I pray,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}asking that, if he be willing, I may some day at last find the way open to visit you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}For I long to see you, in order to impart to you some spiritual gift and so give you fresh strength \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}or rather that both you and I may find encouragement in each other\uc1\u8217*s faith.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}I want you to know, my friends, that I have many times intended coming to see you \uc1\u8211* but until now I have been prevented \uc1\u8211* that I might find among you some fruit of my labours, as I have already among the other nations.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs32 Faith the Ground of Acceptance

\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}I have a duty to both the Greek and the barbarian, to both the cultured and the ignorant.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And so, for my part, I am ready to tell the good news to you also who are in Rome.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}For I am not ashamed of the good news; it is the power of God which brings salvation to everyone who believes, to the Jew first, but also to the Greek.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}For in it there is a revelation of the divine righteousness resulting from faith and leading on to faith; as scripture says \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Through faith the righteous will find life.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}So, too, there is a revelation from heaven of the divine wrath against every form of ungodliness and wickedness on the part of those people who, by their wicked lives, are stifling the truth.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}This is so, because what can be known about God is plain to them; for God himself has made it plain.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}For ever since the creation of the universe God\uc1\u8217*s invisible attributes \uc1\u8211* his everlasting power and divinity \uc1\u8211* are to be seen and studied in his works, so that people have no excuse;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}because, although they learned to know God, yet they did not offer him as God either praise or thanksgiving. Their speculations about him proved futile, and their undiscerning minds were darkened.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Professing to be wise, they showed themselves fools;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}and they transformed the glory of the immortal God into the likeness of mortal humans, and of birds, and beasts, and reptiles.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Therefore God abandoned them to impurity, letting them follow the cravings of their hearts, until they dishonoured their own bodies;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}for they had substituted a lie for the truth about God, and had reverenced and worshiped created things more than the Creator, who is to be praised for ever. Amen.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}That, I say, is why God abandoned them to degrading passions. Even the women among them perverted the natural use of their bodies to the unnatural;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}while the men, disregarding that for which women were intended by nature, were consumed with passion for one another. Men indulged in vile practices with men, and incurred in their own persons the inevitable penalty for their perverseness.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Then, as they would not keep God before their minds, God abandoned them to depraved thoughts, so that they did all kinds of shameful things.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}They revelled in every form of wickedness, evil, greed, vice. Their lives were full of envy, murder, quarrelling, treachery, malice.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}They became back-biters, slanderers, impious, insolent, boastful. They devised new sins. They disobeyed their parents.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}They were undiscerning, untrustworthy, without natural affection or pity.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}Well aware of God\uc1\u8217*s decree, that those who do such things deserve to die, not only are they guilty of them themselves, but they even applaud those who do them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 2}Therefore you have nothing to say in your own defence, whoever you are who set yourself up as a judge. In judging others you condemn yourself, for you who set yourself up as a judge do the very same things.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And we know that God\uc1\u8217*s judgment falls unerringly on those who do them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}You who judge those that do such things and yet are yourself guilty of them \uc1\u8211* do you suppose that you of all people will escape God\uc1\u8217*s judgment?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Or do you think lightly of his abundant kindness, patience, and forbearance, not realising that his kindness is meant to lead you to repentance?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Hard-hearted and impenitent as you are, you are storing up for yourself wrath on the day of wrath, when God\uc1\u8217*s justice as a judge will be revealed;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}for he will give to everyone what their actions deserve.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}To those who, by perseverance in doing good, aim at glory, honour, and all that is imperishable, he will give immortal life;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}while as to those who are factious, and disobedient to truth but obedient to evil, wrath and anger, distress and despair,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}will fall on every human being who persists in wrongdoing \uc1\u8211* on the Jew first, but also on the Greek.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}But there will be glory, honour, and peace for everyone who does right \uc1\u8211* for the Jew first, but also for the Greek,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}since God shows no partiality.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}All who, when they sin, are without Law will also perish without Law; while all who, when they sin, are under Law, will be judged as being under Law.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}It is not those who hear the words of a Law that are righteous before God, but it is those who obey it that will be pronounced righteous.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}When Gentiles, who have no Law, do instinctively what the Law requires, they, though they have no Law, are a Law to themselves;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}for they show the demands of the Law written on their hearts; their consciences corroborating it, while in their thoughts they argue either in self-accusation or, it may be, in self-defence \uc1\u8211*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}on the day when God passes judgment on people\uc1\u8217*s inmost lives, as the good news that I tell declares that he will do through Christ Jesus.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}But, perhaps, you bear the name of \uc1\u8220*Jew,\uc1\u8221* and are relying on Law, and boast of belonging to God, and understand his will,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and, having been carefully instructed from the Law, have learned to appreciate the finer moral distinctions.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Perhaps you are confident that you are a guide to the blind, a light to those who are in the dark, an instructor of the unintelligent,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}and a teacher of the childish, because in the Law you possess the outline of all knowledge and truth.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Why, then, you teacher of others, don\uc1\u8217*t you teach yourself? Do you preach against stealing, and yet steal?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Do you forbid adultery, and yet commit adultery? Do you loathe idols, and yet plunder temples?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Boasting, as you do, of your Law, do you dishonour God by breaking the Law?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}For, as scripture says \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*The Gentiles insult God\uc1\u8217*s name because of you\uc1\u8221*!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Circumcision has its value, if you are obeying the Law. But, if you are a breaker of the Law, your circumcision is no better than uncircumcision.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}If, then, an uncircumcised man pays regard to the requirements of the Law, won\uc1\u8217*t he, although not circumcised, be regarded by God as if he were?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}Indeed, the person who, owing to his birth, remains uncircumcised, and yet scrupulously obeys the Law, will condemn you, who, for all your written Law and your circumcision, are yet a breaker of the Law.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}For a man who is only a Jew outwardly is not a real Jew; nor is outward bodily circumcision real circumcision. The real Jew is the person who is a Jew in soul;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}and the real circumcision is the circumcision of the heart, a spiritual and not a literal thing. Such a person wins praise from God, though not from people.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 3}What is the advantage, then, of being a Jew? Or what is the good of circumcision?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Great in every way. First of all, because the Jews were entrusted with God\uc1\u8217*s utterances.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}What follows then? Some, no doubt, showed a want of faith; but will their want of faith make God break faith? Heaven forbid!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}God must prove true, though everyone prove a liar! As scripture says of God \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*That you may be pronounced righteous in what you say, and gain your cause when people would judge you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}But what if our wrongdoing makes God\uc1\u8217*s righteousness all the clearer? Will God be wrong in inflicting punishment? (I can but speak as a person.) Heaven forbid!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Otherwise how can God judge the world?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}But, if my falsehood redounds to the glory of God, by making his truthfulness more apparent, why am I like others, still condemned as a sinner?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Why should we not say \uc1\u8211* as some people slanderously assert that we do say \uc1\u8211* \uc1\u8220*Let us do evil that good may come\uc1\u8221*? The condemnation of such people is indeed just!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}What follows, then? Are we Jews in any way superior to others? Not at all. Our indictment against both Jews and Greeks was that all alike were in subjection to sin.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}As scripture says \uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard
\par}

